{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_017o4A85JAtSgKruvSNu6J6y","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Let me analyze each behavior carefully using the decision framework provided.\n\n**Behavior 1: An image containing explicit content is flagged and held for review, not published.**\n\n- MOCK-MISS: This behavior involves the AI vision model classifying an image. The failure mode is whether the AI model correctly identifies explicit content and the pipeline correctly routes it to \"held for review.\" This requires a real AI model call to meaningfully test.\n- REAL-INFRA: Doesn't necessarily require OS/network unless testing against a real API.\n- LLM-DEP: Yes - correctness depends on what a real AI vision model produces. The classification of explicit content depends on actual AI model output.\n\n\n- MULTI-STEP: Just one AI step (vision classification) followed by routing logic.\n- Minimum level: Agentic - because the correctness depends on what the real AI vision model produces.\n\n**Behavior 2: A text post containing hate speech is flagged regardless of obfuscation techniques (e.g., letter substitution, unicode lookalikes).**\n\n- MOCK-MISS: This tests whether the AI text model can detect obfuscated hate speech. This is fundamentally about AI model capability.\n- LLM-DEP: Yes - correctness depends on what the real AI text model produces. The model's robustness to obfuscation is the behavior being tested.\n- MULTI-STEP: Just one AI step.\n- Minimum level: Agentic - the test's validity hinges on the real text model's ability to handle obfuscation patterns.\n\n**Behavior 3: A post that passes both content checks is published rather than held or silently dropped.**\n\n- MOCK-MISS: This tests the routing logic that publishes posts after both checks pass. Since I can mock both AI models to return \"clean\", the failure mode is purely in the decision logic, not the AI itself.\n- INTEGRATION-CHECK: The core issue is whether the system correctly publishes when both checks pass. This involves the pipeline wiring after both models return their results, so it's more than a single unit test - it requires testing the module-level routing behavior.\n- I'll classify this as Integration with mocked AI models, since the failure mode is in how the pipeline coordinates the two checks and makes the publish decision.\n\n**Behavior 4: The full moderation pipeline completes within 5 seconds of submission.**\n\n- This is a performance test that requires measuring actual latency across the entire pipeline.\n- Mocking the AI models won't reveal real bottlenecks since the latency depends on actual API calls and network behavior. I need to test with real AI model calls to catch realistic timing issues, which makes this Agentic or System level depending on whether the focus is on AI response time or pure infrastructure performance.\n- The 5-second requirement is really about infrastructure performance rather than classification accuracy, so I could potentially use a real HTTP stub server with realistic latency instead of actual AI models. But the spec mentions \"full moderation pipeline,\" which suggests I need realistic behavior including the AI components.\n- I'm leaning toward Agentic since the AI model latency is integral to the pipeline, though there's a case for System level if I'm just testing with a realistic mock service.\n\nFor the vision model unavailability test, I'm looking at error handling and retry queue logic when the AI service fails. The question is whether I need real infrastructure or if a mock error response would suffice to validate the retry behavior.\n\nThis feels like an Integration test—I can mock the vision model to throw an error and verify the post gets queued for retry without needing the actual AI service. The failure mode involves the pipeline's error handling, but not real model responses.\n\nFor the consistency test with borderline images, I'm now considering whether the same image submitted multiple times should produce identical moderation decisions.  This really depends on the AI model's actual behavior with borderline cases, so mocking won't work—I need the real model to see if it's deterministic. The multiple submissions in sequence suggest this could be Workflow, but it's really just repeated Agentic calls checking consistency rather than different pipeline steps.\n\nNow I'm settling on my final categorizations and moving into the probability assessments.\n\nFor the explicit image flagging behavior, I'm assigning high weight to Agentic testing since it fundamentally depends on the real vision model's accuracy—unit and integration tests with mocks won't catch actual classification failures. The obfuscated hate speech similarly needs the real text model to validate robustness. The clean post publishing is primarily an integration concern around routing logic. The 5-second completion time is a system-level test with stubbed AI latency. Vision model unavailability and queueing is integration-focused error handling. And the borderline image consistency requires running the real model multiple times to account for non-determinism.\n\nNow I'm working through the probability distributions for each behavior across test levels, starting with the vision-based behaviors that heavily favor Agentic testing, then moving into the integration-heavy routing scenario. Now I'm sketching out the actual test cases—starting with an explicit image that should trigger a \"held for review\" decision from a real vision model, then obfuscated hate speech variants that the text classifier needs to catch, followed by a clean post that passes both moderation checks and reaches published state, and finally a latency test against a stub service to verify the 5-second SLA.\n\nI also need to handle the failure case where the vision model goes down, ensuring posts queue for retry instead of auto-approving, and then verify that a borderline image produces consistent decisions across multiple rapid submissions rather than flip-flopping.\n\nNow I'm mapping each test to its test type—the real AI models make these agentic tests, the mocked ones are integration, and the stub service with realistic latency is system-level.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":3,"cache_creation_input_tokens":9645,"cache_read_input_tokens":3199,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":9645},"output_tokens":0,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"e957030f-170f-489b-8f7c-2e48fd4982b6","uuid":"f63de16e-e96e-483b-aa87-b824f788c25f"}
{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_017o4A85JAtSgKruvSNu6J6y","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01BmWxVgCgevaAqByohkUHwF","name":"StructuredOutput","input":{"behaviors":[{"behavior_id":1,"description":"An image containing explicit content is flagged and held for review, not published.","minimum_level":"Agentic","justification":"MOCK-MISS: The failure mode is that the AI vision model fails to classify explicit content correctly. LLM-DEP: A mocked model always returns whatever the test author hardcodes — it cannot reveal whether the real model actually flags explicit images. The classification correctness is the whole point of this behavior. INTEGRATION-CHECK does not apply because the failure is not at a module boundary; it is inside the AI model's judgment. MULTI-STEP: Only one AI step, so Workflow is not needed.","test_description":"Submit a set of known-explicit reference images (curated ground-truth corpus) to the full moderation pipeline backed by the real AI vision model. Assert that each image results in a 'held for review' decision and that no explicit image reaches 'published' state.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.02,"Integration":0.05,"System":0.06,"Agentic":0.8,"Workflow":0.07}},{"behavior_id":2,"description":"A text post containing hate speech is flagged regardless of obfuscation techniques (e.g., letter substitution, unicode lookalikes).","minimum_level":"Agentic","justification":"LLM-DEP: Robustness to obfuscation is a property of the real AI text model's generalization, not of any pipeline wiring. A mocked classifier will trivially 'detect' whatever strings the test author lists, hiding the real failure — that the model may not generalize to novel obfuscation variants. MOCK-HIDE: mocking always passes here. The behavior is testing AI model capability, not control-flow correctness.","test_description":"Construct a suite of hate-speech payloads with systematic obfuscations (unicode homoglyphs, leet-speak, zero-width characters, mixed-script substitution). Send each through the pipeline with the real AI text classifier active. Assert every variant receives a 'flagged' classification and is held for review.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.02,"Integration":0.04,"System":0.05,"Agentic":0.84,"Workflow":0.05}},{"behavior_id":3,"description":"A post that passes both content checks is published rather than held or silently dropped.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"MOCK-MISS: The failure mode is a routing or state-machine bug — the pipeline drops or mis-routes a post after both models return 'pass'. This is a cross-module wiring defect, not an AI classification defect. INTEGRATION-CHECK Down-test: if the publish decision lives in a single function taking two boolean results, Unit suffices; but the behavior explicitly frames the failure as the combined outcome of both checks feeding into a publish decision, which requires the two module boundaries to be wired. MOCK-HIDE: mocking both AI models to return 'clean' is correct here — the failure being tested is in the routing logic, not the model output. Real AI is not needed.","test_description":"Wire the image-classification module and text-classification module together with in-process fakes that return 'approved'. Submit a post through the combined pipeline and assert the post transitions to 'published' state, that no hold event is emitted, and that the post is not silently absent from the output.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.28,"Integration":0.57,"System":0.08,"Agentic":0.05,"Workflow":0.02}},{"behavior_id":4,"description":"The full moderation pipeline completes within 5 seconds of submission.","minimum_level":"System","justification":"REAL-INFRA: The 5-second SLA is a wall-clock latency requirement over the full pipeline. Latency depends on OS scheduling, real network I/O to the AI model endpoints, queue implementation, and concurrency behavior under load. In-process fakes eliminate the network and scheduling effects that are the primary failure mode. LLM-DEP: The SLA test does not need real AI classification correctness — a stub service with realistic response-time characteristics (e.g., 200–800 ms per call) is sufficient and avoids non-determinism. Therefore System is the minimum; Agentic is not required.","test_description":"Deploy the moderation service as a real subprocess against stub AI model endpoints (controllable latency injection, e.g., 400 ms per call). Submit a batch of posts and measure wall-clock time from submission acknowledgement to final decision emission. Assert the 99th-percentile latency is under 5 seconds. Parameterize stub latency to confirm the SLA holds even at the high end of expected model response time.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.01,"Integration":0.09,"System":0.62,"Agentic":0.25,"Workflow":0.03}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"When the AI vision model is unavailable, image posts are queued for retry rather than auto-approved.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"MOCK-MISS: The failure mode is an error-handling and routing defect — the pipeline auto-approves or drops a post when the model client throws a connection/timeout error, instead of enqueuing it. This is a cross-module defect: the model client, the error handler, and the retry queue must all interact correctly. INTEGRATION-CHECK Down-test: cannot reproduce by calling one function, because the failure appears only when the model client error propagates through the pipeline to the queue writer. Up-test: no real OS/network behavior is needed — a fake model client that raises a connection error is sufficient to trigger the real failure path. Real AI is irrelevant (LLM-DEP: no).","test_description":"Configure the vision model client with an in-process fake that raises a connection error on every call. Submit an image post through the moderation pipeline. Assert that no 'approved' or 'published' event is emitted, that the post appears in the retry queue with correct metadata, and that no exception escapes the pipeline boundary.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.14,"Integration":0.68,"System":0.13,"Agentic":0.03,"Workflow":0.02}},{"behavior_id":6,"description":"The moderation decision for a borderline image is consistent when the same image is submitted multiple times within a short window.","minimum_level":"Agentic","justification":"LLM-DEP: Consistency for borderline cases is a property of real AI model non-determinism — temperature, sampling, and model versioning can cause different decisions on repeated calls for ambiguous inputs. A mocked model is always deterministic by construction and will trivially pass, hiding the real failure. MOCK-HIDE: any mock always agrees with itself, so the test would never catch genuine flip-flopping. MULTI-STEP: While this requires multiple pipeline submissions, all steps are the same (repeated classification of one image), not distinct sequential agentic steps in a workflow, so Workflow is not the minimum level.","test_description":"Select a set of images that have been empirically identified as borderline (near the model's decision boundary, previously causing inconsistent outputs). Submit each image to the moderation pipeline backed by the real AI vision model at least 5 times in rapid succession. Assert that all decisions for a given image agree (all 'flagged' or all 'approved'). Flag any image where decisions diverge as a consistency violation.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.01,"Integration":0.03,"System":0.04,"Agentic":0.67,"Workflow":0.25}}]},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":3,"cache_creation_input_tokens":9645,"cache_read_input_tokens":3199,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":9645},"output_tokens":0,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"e957030f-170f-489b-8f7c-2e48fd4982b6","uuid":"eff80e48-e4c3-47a4-b8ee-0a069d6832ab"}
